76561197993862065,Recommended,259550,32314694,Posted: 10 June,all,IceHippo,"A few hours of low-brainpower point and click, if you get it on deep discount (such as the Steam Summer sale) it has great value for the moneyTL;DR -- This game has about the mental exertion of Minesweeper, making it both a good game for young children and also for those adults that need a minimal-brainpower break. Get it on big discount only.The setting is a fantasy kingdom, and you are a young farmer who's trying to figure out what happend to your father. There are bandits, wild animals, and other tasks. Clickable locations on the map are marked, indicating things like places for resource  gathering (fish, animals, etc). A good part of the game is finding hidden resources, represented by tiny icons (like a hidden object game). There are no logic puzzles, timed puzzles, or random combat. The story is cliche', about what a child would write for a creative writing assignment.The rest of the game is resource management. You have health and money. Strenuous tasks cost health, which you can replenish by resting and consuming food. You can buy and sell items are certian locations. In order to complete certain tasks (including battles) you need specific amounts of items. All the needed items are spelled out for you when the task becomes available, so that you spend the next bit of game play trying to come up with the right mix of items to complete the task. Getting this right mix of items is where the resource management comes in. You spend quite a bit of time finding raw items (such as by hunting, fishing, or gathering herbs) and converting them into finished items or money. As your characer gains experience, more items are able to be found.The whole thing could either be a game teaching young children about resource management games (with lots of hidden objects) or a game for weary adults needing a mental break. About the first 15 minutes of gameplay is very straight forward, as you have everything to complete them and are just clicking through, but soon you come to tasks that require you to do some resource management, above.Once you finishe the game, you can go for 100% achievements, but the pixel hunting to collect all the eggs/crates/mushrooms is not easy.This game is cheap and periodically goes on heavy discount. I got it for $0.50, if I sell all the cards it'll be cheaper. It's maybe 4 hours of very low brainpower investment, and thus a very good value/cost ratio. I'm certainly going to investigate the sequel on the store page (but I'll only get it on 50% or better discount)."
